comment.text: This is the armorial bookplate of Boies Penrose, Jr. (1902-1976). Notwithstanding the suffix, he was the nephew (and not the son) of Boies Penrose, the colorful and corrupt Republican political boss of Pennsylvania of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, who was the U.S. Senator for Pennsylvania from 1897-1921 and the source of a few must-read quips about politics which can be found on his wikipedia page. [1] Boies Penrose, Jr., was the son of Dr. Charles Bingham Penrose, a Professor of Surgery at the University of Pennsylvania, and Katherine Drexel Penrose. He was born on November 20, 1902. As a scion of the Drexel family, he did not need to engage in business, and devoted his life to scholarly pursuits, including collecting books, manuscripts, and maps with an emphasis on Tudor and Stuart times. He sold part of his collection through Sotheby's in 1971, and the catalog was suitably entitled The Celebrated Library of Boies Penrose Esq, FSA, FRGS. He lectured at St. John's College in Annapolis and at Ursinus College, receiving an honorary doctorate in literature from Ursinus in 1953 and serving on its Board a few years later. Among his other accomplishments was his long association with the Historical Society of Pennsylvania (HSP), including 15 years as its President. After his death in February 1976, the HSP published a wonderful biographical sketch, from which the above information is only a small sample [2]. As an author, he is listed in VIAF. The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography, Vol. 100, No. 3 (Jul., 1976), pp. 390-394. www.jstor.org/stable/20091081 [3] viaf.org/viaf/61927977/

comment.text: This is most likely the bookplate of William Pepper, Jr., M.D. (August 21, 1843 - July 28, 1898). comment.text: Bookplate of Iva Gilbertson Foster (1891-1950) This bookplate, with the picture of a young child, is a plaintive echo of the sad tale of the life of Iva Gilbertson Foster. Born on March 18, 1891 in Iowa [1], she was the wife of a millionaire meat packer, John Morrell Foster of the Morrell meat packing family of South Dakota. [2] Together, they adopted a son, Whitney Foster (b. 1927), but then divorced in March 1933. Custody of Whitney Foster was divided between the two parents, with Iva assigned the summer months and his father the remainder of the year. Iva moved to Beverly Hills, California and once her son had joined her there in 1934, waged a celebrated interstate custody battle -- extending from the California and South Dakota courts to the US Supreme Court -- which she ultimately lost in 1937. [3] She lived on in Beverly Hills, but ran out of money and committed suicide on November 10, 1950, by running a vacuum cleaner hose from the exhaust pipe of her car into the passenger compartment. She was found dead on November 11, according to a press report, with the car radio blaring "I'm the Lonesomest Girl in Town." [2] --- [1] State of California. California Death Index, 1940-1997. Sacramento, CA, USA: State of California Department of Health Services, Center for Health Statistics. Now a database on www.ancestry.com. Entry for Iva Gilbertson Foster in the latter contains both her birth and death dates and locations. [2] "Destitute Ex-Wife of Millionaire Dead--A Suicide," Ada [OK] Evening News, November 12, 1950, page 2. newspaperarchive.com/ada-evening-news/1950-11-12/page-2 [3] Foster v. comment.text:
This is the bookplate of Jacob Chester Chamberlain, who was born in India on July 3, 1860, and who died in New York on July 28, 1905. He graduated with honors from Rutgers College in New Jersey in 1882, and subsequently became a pioneer in the development and application of electricity, and with the income from his patents and industrial positions, became one of the pre-eminent collectors of his time of first editions of early American authors. He was also an accomplished and experienced genealogist, and his passing was noted by a fine appreciation in the Memoirs of the New England Historic Genealogical Society:
"Yet his highest excellence was not in his notable electrical discoveries and achievements; nor in his marked business success; nor in his skilful, important work as bibliophile and genealogist. His highest worth was in his character and personal culture. He was faithful to the welfare of both his city and his country. In him gentleness was blended with strength, and amiableness with resolute integrity. Well born and well brought up, he appeared, even to those who knew him most intimately, to have no remotest inclination to any form of dishonor. Comely, courteous, joyous, with a genius for friendship, he was the light of his beautiful home, a centre of attraction among many acquaintances, and an example of perfect uprightness in wide business relations. He was, all in all, a Christian gentleman of rarely noble type." [1]
He is also listed in VIAF. [2] ----- [1] The New England Historical and Genealogical Register, Supplement to the April Number 1906. comment.text: "Ex Libris "Leonia S. Olschki "Bibliopolae Veneti" This is the bookplate of Leo Samuel Olschki (1861-1940), an antiquarian bookseller born in the Polish portion of East Prussia to a family of Jewish printers. He moved to Italy and founded a publishing house known as "Libreria Antiquaria Editrice" ("Antiquarian Bookshop Publishers") in 1886 in Verona. Its first work was a catalog of incunabula. In 1890, Olschki moved his firm to Venice and in 1897, he moved it to Florence.[1] This bookplate, with its description of "Bibliopolae Veneti" (Venetian Booksellers), indicates that the book in which it was found was acquired by Olschki between 1890-1897. Olschki has an entry in the Oxford Companion to the Book [2], which perhaps someone with library access can use for more information on his life and work. Olschki also has an entry in VIAF.[3] ------ [1] it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_S._Olschki [2] www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.2011080... [3] viaf.org/viaf/51869824/

comment.text:
Ms. ownership inscription of Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786):
"Theophili Pauli Christii Coburgensis Onoldibati[?] a C.N. MDCCLX."

Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786), professor, librarian and court functionary at Ansbach.
In their finding aid Aldine Press Books at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center, The University of Texas at Austin (Austin: The Center, 1998), Craig W. Kallendorf and Maria X. Wells identify the ex-libris "Theophili Pauli Christi" as "Gottlieb Paul Christ (18th cent.), prof. at Anspach Gymnasium". According to his biographical entry in C.A. Baader, Lexikon Verstorbener Schrifsteller des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts (Augsburg: Von Jenisch- und Stage'schen Buchhandlung, 1825), Bd. 2, T. 1, p. 22, Christ was born in Coburg but came to Ansbach in 1728 to take service with Freiherr von Seckendorff (probably Christoph Ludwig Freiherr von Seckendorff-Aberdar). He went abroad on several diplomatic missions and became the librarian for the Ansbacher Schlossbibliothek. (According to E.F.C. Oertel in Georg Ludwig Oeder der erste Rektor bei der Einweihung des neuen Gymnasiums in Ansbach am 12. Juni 1737 ... (Ansbach: Oertel, 1837) p. 54-55, he got the job in 1738; according to the Schlossbibliothek's history web page, he was the second librarian to be appointed.) In 1737 he was appointed professor at the gymnasium in Ansbach and published a number of works on historical subjects; he also continued to serve at court as a councillor.

comment.author: 65030572@N05
comment.text: "Library of John W. Harshberger "Nov 16 1923 "Inter Folia Fructus" This bookplate, with its mix of biological and Native American motifs and its Latin motto of "between the leaves of the fruit," belongs to John William Harshberger, well-known botanist and Professor of Botany at the University of Pennsylvania. He was born in Philadelphia on January 1, 1869 and died in Philadelphia on April 27, 1929 [1]. His biographical sketch in the online collection guide in the Penn Archives (which houses his papers) summarizes the breadth of his botanical career as follows: "As a botanist, Harshberger traveled widely in North America. He botanized in Eastern and Northwestern states, Southern Florida, Alaska, Arizona, Utah, and California. Overseas, his research trips extended through Europe, Brazil, Argentine, Chile and Mexico."[2] He was the author of the Phytogeographic Survey of North America,[1] and coined the term "ethnobotany" in 1895. [3][4] Given these broad interests, it is not surprising to see a combination of ethnological and biological elements in his bookplate. The handwritten date of November 16, 1923 on the bookplate is consistent with his known dates of birth and death. His accepted American form on viaf [5]: Harshberger, John W. comment.author: 65030572@N05
comment.text: The bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (17 December 1861 – 28 March 1943), a writer, scientist, and Persian scholar, who produced a literal translation of the Quatrians of Omar Khayyam from the earliest known manuscript, which was in the Bodelian Library of Oxford University [1]. Another biographical sketch of him can be found on website maintained by the Heron-Allen Society [2]. The design elements of the bookplate illustrate a number of his interests. He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in May 1919 for his work in studying the Foraminifera, a class of microscopic amoeboid protists that produce their own shells, sometime with multiple chambers. Hence, the owl (symbol of learning), the microscope, and flanking his name, two examples of Foraminifera (compare to the samples in this photograph). He was an expert in the art of palmistry, and wrote several books on the subject, hence the palms at 9 and 3 o'clock of the circular device. As a young man, he learned the art of violin-making, and wrote a book on that topic, as well, hence the violin in the foreground. He was a scholar of Persian and translated the works of Omar Khayyam, and so Persian written in Arabic script appears in the bookplate, as well. He is also known as the author (under the pseudonym of Christopher Blayre) of The Cheetah Girl, a book that was suppressed because it dealt with themes of unconventional sexuality. Perhaps that is why a naked woman is being contemplated by the man in Persian garb. Given the fact that he wrote numerous books, he is found in VIAF. comment.text: "Ex libris Franc Com a Thun Hohenstein Tetschen" This is the armorial book plate of Franz, Count of Thun-Hohenstein, Tetschen, in Bohemia. He was born in Tetschen, Bohemia (now Děčín in the Czech Republic) on September 2, 1847 and died in the same city on November 1, 1916. He served as the Austro-Hungarian Empire's Governor of his native Bohemia from 1889 to 1896 and again from 1911 to 1915. He was also briefly the 15th Minister-President of Austria and Minister of the Interior from 1898 to 1899.[1] He was recognized for his services to the Austro-Hungarian Empire by being raised to princely rank (Furst) in by Kaiser Franz-Josef on July 1911. Given that this bookplate has his earlier rank as a count (Graf), it would have dated before this time. He is listed in VIAF [2].
